<br>
The 20 foot target is exactly the point. Who would have thought &quot;anyone&quot; could have trouble with that? First I took equipment that was not really suited to take the test with. Looking back I can see several mistakes I made even before I got started. You'll need to work on casting skills that are fairly well across the board. The test is more about fundamentals than specific skills. Like you said how long has it been since you carried 40 feet of line with no haul and had to throw &quot;zero&quot; tailing loops. Now do it with a couple of guys watching and grading you.<br>
<br>
The test is not terribly difficult, but it is no cake walk either. Even an accomplished caster like you Andrew will need to prepare before taking it. With that done you'll have no problems at all. You are an excellent caster and will make a wonderful instructor. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :smokin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smokin.gif ALT=":smokin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
John <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=chuckeasterling>chuck easterling</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Casting Corner Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 9<br> <font color=#000000>(2/22/03 5:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> certified casting instruction question</span><hr size=1> Good afternoon Holland,<br>
