<br>
I could almost guarantee that Danny Gaston would bless a casting competition held at their lodge. That is a great idea if you ask me.<br>
<br>
John <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> hauloholic</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#000000>(3/19/03 4:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> CCI Test</span><hr size=1> Andrew --<br>
<br>
From what I've heard, you're a great caster.  It's been 7 or 8 years since I took the test, and I know the format has changed.  When I took it, I finished the written first among 11 total applicants.  It took me almost 2-1/2 hours.  But there were numerous essay questions, and those can take as much time as you want to devote to them.  I actually erased an entire page of writing to say the same thing, more simply.  Kinda like Reverend MacLean telling Norman, &quot;again, half as long....&quot;  Only three applicants passed the written test.<br>
<br>
If I could offer a firm piece of advice, please concentrate most of your preparation time analyzing casters and practicing your coaching skills.  As you know, it takes different approaches to communicate effectively with different individuals.  This was the downfall of the other two applicants when I tested.  They were not able to satisfy the Masters administering the oral/performance test that they were proficient at actually instructing others.  They were fine casters, and I believe both of them have been certified since.  I don't think that the ratio of applicants who fail are this low in general, I believe today's applicants are much better prepared than for some of the early tests.<br>
<br>
Truly, I hope it is a cakewalk for you.  This would mean that you're very capable of handling just about any teaching opportunity you'd come across in a relaxed fashion.  From what I've seen, the applicants that have the most difficulty passing the tests, also have the most trouble as an effective casting instructor.  Not across the board, but generally.  The more confident (not cocky) you are in your skill testing and instruction testing, the more likely you'll pass with flying colors.<br>
<br>
If you are at Sowbug next weekend, I hope to meet you.  Good luck.  TAM<br>
<br>
P.S. - The entire written and two practical tests that I took in 95 lasted at least 5 hours or more total.  Maybe three hours one day, and then 2 hours on another day. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFFF><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=flyfishar>FlyFishAR</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 163<br> <font color=#000000>(3/19/03 8:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://boards.justflies.com/Images/4/4551Photo1.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: CCI Test</span><hr size=1> TAM:<br>
